@SR4ven I didn't realize how difficult this bit would be! The old implementation manually mucks with the Group primitive's values. The new implementation doesn't quite work that way. This is actually an instance where we want to mutate two primitives at one time. Great time to try it out!

In Fuzzable.get_mutations, see this excerpt:
```
            for value in itertools.chain(self.mutations(self.original_value()), self._fuzz_values):
                if self._halt_mutations:
                    self._halt_mutations = False
                    return
                if isinstance(value, Mutation):
                    yield value
                else:
                    yield Mutation(mutations={self.qualified_name: value})
```
Especially the last 4 lines --  the mutations method can either render a value (a bytes object), or a Mutation object. The Mutation.muations field is a map from qualified names to mutated values. get_mutations will always normalize the mutation into a `Mutation` object.

So, you can in Block create a Mutation object, add the Group mutation (`"qualified_group_name": b"the_value"`), then manually add the individual mutation based on what you iterated from the item stack.

Pseudocode:
```
for value in theGroup.mutations():
    m = Mutation(mutations={self.request.resolve_name(self.context_path, self.group): value})  # maybe use self.group.context_path?
    for item in self.stack:
        self.request.mutant = item  # not sure about this -- the "mutant" field starts to become meaningless and may need to be reworked or removed eventually
        for mutation in item.get_mutations():
            # merge mutation.mutations into m.mutations
            yield mutation
```

The new design should in theory support and render these two mutations properly, but there may be bugs to work out.

