@dhslim This part is interesting. You are trying to capture the possibility that *every* statement in the body of the `try` might raise an error, and so dividing up each statement into its own block so that you can connect it to each of the handlers, or the `orelse`.

This currently is inaccurate in two ways: first, some statements might _never_ raise an exception (e.g., `x = 1`), and second, compound statements (e.g., with an `if` block or loop) will be treated as a whole block, rather than being split up as individual statements.

So for now I prefer that you simplify this implementation by _not_ creating a separate block for each statement in the `node.body`, but simply call `child.accept` for every statement in the body, and then connect the resulting block to the different exception handlers and the `orelse`. This is also a simplification, but the benefit is it'll lead to a simpler implementation that we can build on later.

