@pipermerriam thanks for clarifying! FYI the reason why we put validator balances into a separate list in BeaconState (#1647) was clarified [here](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/issues/386#issuecomment-451033847) by Justin:
> It's an optimisation to minimise the amount of hashing when computing the beacon state root. The `validator_registry` (which contains most of the state) changes slowly and requires little hashing effort to maintain. The `validator_balances` is a smaller part of the state with much higher churn, hence why it is segregated.

So I do think this `ValueError` here fits "*for lower level errors, normally indicative of us having some kind of broken code which is passing in the wrong type of value or a malformed value*" since it's for avoiding reckless coding.

This is mostly to make it "nice" (subjectively), I'm really not worried about performance one way or another (untested):
```
if (i < 0) {
    i += v.size();
    if (i < 0) {
        throw index_errror();
    }
}
auto i_st = static_cast<SizeType>(i);
if (i_st >= v.size()) {
    throw index_error();
}
return v[i_st];
```

What's missing here IMO is nice error reporting (e.g. something like "index -8 is out of range for array size 5"), but that's beyond the scope of this PR.

I guess the purpose of this assert is to make sure that `kMessageActionStrings[kMessageSend]` is "Send". However we don't require that `kMessageSend` must be 0. I think it's possible to verify the actual purpose. 

```

constexpr bool strings_equal(char const *a, char const *b)
{
    return *a == *b && (*a == '\0' || strings_equal(a + 1, b + 1));
}

const char *Mle::MessageActionToString(MessageAction aAction)
{
    static constexpr const char *const kMessageActionStrings[] = {
        "Send",           // (0) kMessageSend
        "Receive",        // (1) kMessageReceive
        "Delay",          // (2) kMessageDelay
        "Remove Delayed", // (3) kMessageRemoveDelayed
    };

    static_assert(strings_equal("Send", kMessageActionStrings[kMessageSend]), "kMessageSend value is incorrect");
    static_assert(strings_equal("Receive", kMessageActionStrings[kMessageReceive]),
                  "kMessageReceive value is incorrect");
    static_assert(strings_equal("Delay", kMessageActionStrings[kMessageDelay]), "kMessageDelay value is incorrect");
    static_assert(strings_equal("Remove Delayed", kMessageActionStrings[kMessageRemoveDelayed]),
                  "kMessageRemoveDelayed value is incorrect");

    return kMessageActionStrings[aAction];
}
```

