I have changed the process similarly as suggested:
The `json_to_array.py` python script goes through `/modules` directory and processes all modules that are present there as `.json` (public modules). Each file is split per char and the sequence of chars is written in a new file `module_<name>_generated.h` that contains the following class:
```
class Gmodule_<name> : public ModuleContent
{
public:
	Gmodule_<name>() : ModuleContent("pe", {'{', '\n', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', '\"', 'k', 'i', 'n', 'd', '\"', ':', ' ', '\"', 's', 't', 'r', 'u', 'c', 't',...})
	{
	}
};
```
where `<name>` is shortened name of the input `.json` file and `ModuleContent` is a simple base class prepared to store the sequence. These files are generated in the `/include/yaramod/types/modules/generated` directory together with one additional file `modules_list.h` which includes all generated `.h` modules and creates a vector of `ModuleContent` containing an instance of each of the created modules.

